This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with the problem of non-rigid structure from motion, which is a central problem in computer vision. The paper also presents a benchmark and evaluation of different methods, which is a common practice in the computer vision community. 

The paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as some of the methods evaluated in the benchmark may involve machine learning techniques. 

The robotics (cs.RO) sub-category is also a possibility as non-rigid structure from motion is relevant to robotics applications such as object tracking and manipulation. 

The multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category may also be relevant as the paper deals with obtaining 3D information from multiple images, which is a common task in multimedia applications such as virtual reality and augmented reality. 

Finally, the graphics (cs.GR) sub-category may also be relevant as the paper deals with 3D reconstruction, which is a common task in computer graphics applications such as animation and video game development.
